@MattS

Except the top-to-bottom puzzle answer "IWASFRAMED" acted as the cross-check.
As someone who initially had "IWTSFRAMET", it worked for me.

@HC Tabak 

Speaking logically, I suppose

A painting can be a Monet, hence a Monet can be a painting.

@Emily68 

When the circle around the "i" icon at the top of the screen is flashing, it means there is information available. For Sunday puzzles, you'll see the title, which is often a hint about the trickery involved.

It may also include any notes that a solver might need to help solve, as it does for this puzzle.

@Aug 

Snerd is probably somewhat difficult for those who are more familiar with Candice Bergen than her father Edgar. Edgar was an actor and comedian, but started out as a ventriloquist with his first dummy, Charlie McCarthy, and then added Mortimer Snerd to his acts. He did a lot of radio work in the 40s and 50s and appeared on television during the 50s, 60s and 70s. He also appeared in several films, and his last film role was in the Muppet Movie.

I had a little trouble with Darien, but finally remembered it, as I haven't lived in the New York City area since 1965

@Greg 

Made even more confusing my DALI being stolen from 18A but D finishing off 69D, so it looks like only ALI was stolen.  

A good concept but terrible execution IMO.

@Steve 

I solve all puzzles on mobile.  It wasn’t that awful. At one point I even cleared the board because I was sure I had a mistake. 

It’s all a part of the process.

@Steve 

The answer key is wrong. If you look at the rules of the puzzle by the maker, that portion of the answer was taken out and placed elsewhere.  There is an empty box in that portion of the answer. The only letter you have to answer is the  letter from the crossing down clue. 

Even the word play explains it that way.

@Akiva 

Are you sure?

<a href="https://itgetsbetter.org/glossary/femme-fem" target="_blank">https://itgetsbetter.org/glossary/femme-fem</a>/

@B 

I have never agreed with you more! I was so confused by the implementation of this puzzle's theme - I kept entering and deleting rebuses, and neither made sense. On top of that the fill was really bad in places - dozens of trivia clues, and some of them of the most arcane type for me: musical keys and sports. In the end I just gave up and revealed the puzzle. I've never had less fun dealing with a grid than today.

I don't share your criticism of the constructor though: I don't know them, and I won't judge a person by one crossword puzzle.

@HamR

@HamR

💯% agree. While this was a very creative, original, clever amd (partially/ in theory) fun puzzle, I agree with you. I was definitely grousing towards the end (and the middle) wondering why they couldn't let us bookmark the connection between the artist & the scene of the crime, in BOTH directions. I kept having to troll thru the puzzle to find the artist associated w/the long missing-letters entry, def a bit unnecessarily tedious... def a LOT of flyspecking, it got to be kind of grueling. It was still worth it, & I'm glad I encountered & did this puzzle, but I think it was an unnecessary omission (by the editors, really, who have final say) and IMO it would NOT have made it "too easy" to simply highlight the connection in BOTH directions.

I also felt there were some quite semi-Naticky spots, or upon second glance just muddy spots that were clogged up by that lack of any decent way to doublecheck the associated artist. I got stuck a lot on the whole FEMS/ SM[OKEEFFE]CTS/ TOYMEN knot in the East, only noticing NOW that tje 78D letter was C for COOKIE, duh; I'd kept veering toward LOOKIE and not knowing WHAT the H was goin' on there. But it was still all in all very satisfying to finish it. Tada!

It was very intricate & picayune in solving, making the exlerience sort of like a combination of doing one's taxes & having at a successful satisfying puzzle. Two things at once, kinda like the theme answers in this puzzle.

Stepping back, the solve looks good Vermeer.

@Steve L,

I don’t get what you are saying. The instructions say that the thief took the paintings (referred to by their artists) from the Across and “left behind…letters in the Downs” as evidence. So you skip over the “evidence” when reading across because the paintings are missing from the across answers. Just imagine that that “I” (and other letters like it) are circled, and you only read them literally going Down, while treating them as standing in for something else (the missing paintings) in the Across  — that’s a fairly common trick in crosswords, no?

There were lots of things that were frustrating about the construction, particularly bad fill, but yours doesn’t seem to be a valid complaint.

@Haim Wright 

I know you're a good solver but I'm still impressed you managed to finish this. Respect!

I just gave up after shrugging at all the rebuses I kept entering and deleting for the longest time.

@Barry Ancona 

Wow those goal posts must be heavy.  Just call it what it is, an exception, a really bad, poorly conceived, poorly edited, and poorly presented exception to the norm.

@Brady my pet theory is that this "arbitrary level of money business" was taken to an extreme on purpose to make everyone hate Thursdays.  It's not going to work!  :)

