(emu filler)

@Sebastian

Full disclosure, I'm very happy to lookup words or phrases. I don't live in America so my knowledge of the predominantly US-specific trivia is, though growing, relatively limited. It's a 100x worse with naticks. It isn't a criticism. It is, after all, the New York Times Crossword. But this is the first time I've had to check the Today's Themes section to find what I was doing wrong because after over two hours and a triple-check later, the timer didn't stop. It must be the puzzle's fault, I thought. Grumble, grumble. Sigh, it turns out it was STP, not SAP (superabsorbent polymers are also fuel additives, I'll have you know). But the most embarrassing as a queer man was KENS, instead of FEMS. In my def, I hate abbrvs and only write femme. 

So there you have it, I have no one to blame but myself. I'm a NAIF and a duffer so I'd better avoid all PONDs. Which is apt as I can't swim anyway.

@Super8ing 

C’mon Super8ing. We all know the
New Yorker doesn’t have puzzles on the weekend.

@B. Bussert 

Judging by this timeline, <a href="https://corporate.ford.com/about/history/company-timeline.html" target="_blank">https://corporate.ford.com/about/history/company-timeline.html</a>, it looks like there was an earlier Model A in 1903.  The Model T was the first mass-produced Ford.  After the Model T, there was another Model A in 1927.  Kind of confusing. 

Knowing nothing about cars, I just guessed at the A, and that was confirmed by the hidden message.

@J 

I thought outside the box. I solved it. I didn’t like the basic idea of dropping an extraneous letter into the across answers via the downs that didn’t make any sense at all, and I described that at length in a comment about 7 hours ago. The dropped down letter should have been part of the across phrase that needed to be in there with the missing artist name taken out, not just a random, unnecessary one. 

Today I’m a naysayer, although I solved the puzzle and understood what was going on.

@Steve L 

Yes of course the secret phrase is a way to verify the unchecked letters but I think that’s a stretch from the generally understanding of what a checked crossword entails. 

The weakness in that explanation is that the secret phrase has no clue. It’s determined from the unchecked letters. It can’t be said that the puzzle’s title and theme in and of themselves are a reasonable clue to the phrase.

@Jane Wheelaghan 
Mel Ott was a major league baseball player. He played for the New York Giants (who moved from NY to San Francisco).

A Bodega is a store similar to a deli, mostly in NYC, with a Hispanic connection.  And so much more than that.

